Linear Regression - Evaluation - Residual Plots

Make three residual plots for mod1:

  • plot the residuals against the fitted values
  • plot the residuals against one explanatory variable (smoking)
  • plot the residuals against the other explanatory variable (age)

Notice that I added message = F to the start of my code chunk here to hide the messages that otherwise print out about the geom_smooth function.

# residuals vs fitted
augment(mod1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = .resid, x = .fitted)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) + 
  labs(x = 'Fitted Values', y = 'Residuals', title = 'Residuals vs Fitted Values (Model 1)') + 
  theme_classic() 

# residuals vs smoke
augment(mod1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = .resid, x = smoke)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +  
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) + 
  labs(x = 'Smoking Status', y = 'Residuals', title = 'Residuals vs Explanatory Variable (Model 1)') + 
  theme_classic()

# residuals vs age
augment(mod1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = .resid, x = age)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  labs(x = 'Age', y = 'Residuals', title = 'Residuals vs Explanatory Variable (Model 1)') +
  theme_classic()

What do you notice about these residual plots? Is there any pattern (i.e., is our model systematically under- or over-predicting for certain people)? Is there equal spread of residuals across fitted values and explanatory variables? What does all of this suggest about our model?

I notice a trend that our model tends to over-predict (has negative residuals) for children with large fitted values (i.e., high values of predicted FEV) and children who are older (age > 15 or so).

I don’t notice a particularly strong pattern with smoking: the median residual is slightly below zero for nonsmokers and slightly above zero for smokers, but both medians are quite close to zero. This suggest to me that there isn’t any tendency for our model to systematically over- or under-estimating FEV for either of these groups.

The spread of the residuals seems like it could perhaps be increasing slightly as fitted values and ages increase (i.e., we see a bit of a fanning out pattern). The spread of the residuals is also a bit wider for smokers than it is for nonsmokers. Having a wider spread of our residuals suggests that more of our predictions are farther “off” (residuals far from zero, in either direction) for kids that are older, have higher predicted FEV, and/or smoke — our model isn’t as consistently good at predicting for these kids.

Linear Regression - Evaluation - Model Quality Metrics

Calculate the R-squared and residual standard error for both models.

# metrics for mod1
glance(mod1)
## # A tibble: 1 × 12
##   r.squared adj.r.squared sigma statistic   p.value    df logLik   AIC   BIC
##       <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.577         0.575 0.565      443. 3.25e-122     2  -553. 1114. 1132.
## # … with 3 more variables: deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>
# metrics for mod2
glance(mod2)
## # A tibble: 1 × 12
##   r.squared adj.r.squared sigma statistic   p.value    df logLik   AIC   BIC
##       <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.594         0.592 0.554      317. 8.66e-127     3  -539. 1089. 1111.
## # … with 3 more variables: deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>

Which model has a better R-squared? Which model has a better residual standard error?

We want R-squared to be high (closer to 1) and residual standard error to be low (closer to 0). It looks like mod2 is best according to both of these metrics.

Write down an interpretation of the R-squared, in the context of the data, for whichever model you decided was best.

Suppose we said mod2 was best.

The R-squared of 0.594 tells us that this model explains 59.4% of the variation in FEV.

Note: adjusted R-squared does not have this same contextually-meaningful interpretation, so make sure you are interpreting R-squared rather than adjusted R-squared.

Write down an interpretation fo the residual standard error, in the context of the data, for whichever model you decided was best.

The residual standard error of 0.554 gives us a sense of the “typical” size of our residuals (i.e., how far off do our predictions tend to be?). The residual standard error is the standard deviation of our residuals. It turns out that the mean of our residuals will always be zero. So, our residual standard error gives us a sense of how tightly concentrated all of our residuals are around zero, which in turn tells us how tightly concentrated our predictions are around the true values. Ideally, we want to see a small value here. There is a useful rule of thumb that tells us that, if our data are normally distributed, 95% of observations will fall within 2 standard deviations of the mean. Applying this rule to our residual standard error, we can say that our model predicts FEV for most kids within 1.108 liters per second. Considering that FEV of kids in this dataset ranges from about 1 up to 6, does being off by 1.1 liters/second seem like a lot?

Linear Regression - Model Creation

Based on your work in Activity 18, what did you decide to use as your final model to answer the research question: what is the impact of smoking on lung function in children? Write down the model equation, using correct notation, below.

There is more than one correct answer here! Different groups may have arrived at different final models depending on their background knowledge on this topic, their opinion about the trade-offs between complexity of the model and ease of interepretation, etc.

At minimum, your model should have FEV as the outcome and smoking status as one of the explanatory variables. Without this, our model will not address our research question. Notation for this simple linear regression model would look like this:

\[E[FEV | smoke] = \beta_0 + \beta_1 smokesmoker\]

However, we almost certainly need to include height and/or age in our model as well. As we’ve discussed in class, we have reason to believe that both age and height are causally associated with FEV among children: older kids will have more developed lungs (and be taller) and thus have better lung function, and taller kids will have larger lungs and thus have better lung function. We also have reason to believe that age would be associated with smoking in our sample, both based on scientific context (older kids are more likely to smoke, and after you turn 18 smoking is legal in many places) and our investigation of these data (we have in fact confirmed that kids who smoke tend to be older than those who don’t). Similarly, we might also expect that kids who smoke tend to be taller in this sample (because they are older). Finally, we know that smoking does not cause changes in age or height. So it seems reasonable that height and/or FEV could be confounding variables! Notation for a multiple linear regression model that adjusts for one or both of these variables as potential confounders would look like this:

\[\text{Just age: }E[FEV | smoke, age] = \beta_0 + \beta_1 smokesmoker + \beta_2 age\]

\[\text{Just height: }E[FEV | smoke, height] = \beta_0 + \beta_1 smokesmoker + \beta_2 height\]

\[\text{Both age and height: }E[FEV | smoke, age, height] = \beta_0 + \beta_1 smokesmoker + \beta_2 age + \beta_3 height\]

As we’ve discussed in class, it also seems plausible that age could be an effect modifier here. The effect of smoking on lung function might differ depending on how old you are, and vice versa, the effect of age on lung function might differ depending on whether or not you smoke. Adjusting for age as an effect modifier, our model would need to include an interaction term as well:

\[\text{Age as an effect modifier: }E[FEV | smoke, age] = \beta_0 + \beta_1 smokesmoker + \beta_2 age + \beta_3 (smokesmoker * age)\]

If you thought that any other variables might be an effect modifier, you would want to include them in your model in this way: both with a main effect for that variable (e.g., \(\beta_2 age\)) and with the interaction between that variable and smoking (e.g., \(\beta_3 (smokesmoker*age)\)). If you thought that any other variables were a confounder (associated with both FEV and smoking) or precision variable (associated with FEV but not smoking), then you would include them in your model using just a main effect, no interaction. Any variables that you identified as a collider, mediator, or irrelevant should be left out of the model.

Another consideration in choosing which variables to include in a model is redundancy/multicollinearity. If there are two variables in our model that capture very similar information this can be redundant and actually pose problems for statistical inference. If this is the case, choose just one of these variables to include in your model.

Explain/justify your choice of model. Make sure to explain why you decided to include (or exclude) each variable in the way that you did.

Similar to my answers above, your explanation/justification for your choice of model should clearly explain why you included each variable that you did in your model. Is it necessary for answering your research question? Is it a potential confounder, effect modifier, or precision variable? Your justification should match the model you fit. If you described a variable as a potential effect modifier, then your model should include an interaction term. Otherwise, it should not.

Since there are not many variables in this dataset, it is also useful to discuss why you did not include a variable in your model. Is it a potential collider or mediator? Is it redundant with another variable(s) that you did include in the model? Did you feel that the variable was entirely unrelated to our outcome, FEV?

\(R^2\): eport and interpret R-squared (% of variation in Y that can be explained by the model). Note: adjusted R-squared does not have the same nice interpretation that ordinary R-squared does. Residual standard error: report and interpret RSE (our model can predict the outcome within 2*RSE units; the RSE is (roughly) the average magnitude of the residuals/prediction errors)

Takeaway message: does the model meet all conditions (straight enough, equal spread, no extreme outliers) or does it fail to meet one or more of these conditions? based on the R-squared (which we want to be large) and the residual standard error (which we want to be small), is this a good model?
